algorithmSettings.name: failed_f_value
algorithmSettings.description: Return Value for F(x) if F fails

measures.name: residential_simulation_controls
measures.description: Set the simulation timesteps per hour, the run period begin month/day and end month/day, and the calendar year (for start day of week).
measures.modeler_description: Set the simulation timesteps per hour on the Timestep object, the run period begin month/day and end month/day on the RunPeriod object, and the calendar year on the YearDescription object.

arguments.name: timesteps_per_hr
arguments.description: The value entered here is the number of (zone) timesteps to use within an hour. For example a value of 6 entered here directs the program to use a zone timestep of 10 minutes and a value of 60 means a 1 minute timestep.

arguments.name: begin_month
arguments.description: This numeric field should contain the starting month number (1 = January, 2 = February, etc.) for the annual run period desired.

arguments.name: begin_day_of_month
arguments.display_name: Run Period Begin Day of Month
arguments.description: This numeric field should contain the starting day of the starting month (must be valid for month) for the annual run period desired.

arguments.name: end_month
arguments.description: This numeric field should contain the ending month number (1 = January, 2 = February, etc.) for the annual run period desired.

arguments.name: end_day_of_month
arguments.display_name: Run Period End Day of Month
arguments.description: This numeric field should contain the ending day of the ending month (must be valid for month) for the annual run period desired.

arguments.name: calendar_year
arguments.description: This numeric field should contain the calendar year that determines the start day of week. If you are running simulations using AMY weather files, the value entered for calendar year will not be used; it will be overridden by the actual year found in the AMY weather file.

measures.name: hpxml_translator
measures.description: Translates HPXML file to OpenStudio Model

arguments.name: hpxml_path
arguments.description: Absolute (or relative) path of the HPXML file.

arguments.name: weather_dir
arguments.description: Absolute path of the weather directory.

arguments.name: schemas_dir
arguments.description: Absolute path of the hpxml schemas directory.

arguments.name: epw_output_path
arguments.description: Absolute (or relative) path of the output EPW file.

arguments.name: osm_output_path
arguments.description: Absolute (or relative) path of the output OSM file.

arguments.name: skip_validation
arguments.description: If true, only checks for and reports HPXML validation issues if an error occurs during processing. Used for faster runtime.

arguments.name: map_tsv_dir
arguments.description: Creates TSV files in the specified directory that map some HPXML object names to EnergyPlus object names. Required for ERI calculation.

measures.name: residential_geometry_from_floorspace_js
measures.description: Imports a floorplan JSON file written by the FloorspaceJS tool. Sets the number of bedrooms, bathrooms, and occupants in the building. See https://github.com/NREL/OpenStudio-BuildStock#workflows for supported workflows using this measure.
measures.modeler_description: Currently this measure deletes the existing geometry and replaces it. Also, sets (or replaces) BuildingUnit objects that store the number of bedrooms and bathrooms associated with the model. Sets (or replaces) the People object for each finished space in the model.

arguments.name: floorplan_path
arguments.description: Path to the floorplan JSON.

arguments.name: num_bedrooms
arguments.description: Specify the number of bedrooms. Used to determine the energy usage of appliances and plug loads, hot water usage, mechanical ventilation rate, etc.

arguments.name: num_bathrooms
arguments.description: Specify the number of bathrooms. Used to determine the hot water usage, etc.

arguments.name: num_occupants
arguments.description: Specify the number of occupants. A value of 'auto' will calculate the average number of occupants from the number of bedrooms. Used to specify the internal gains from people only.

arguments.name: occupants_weekday_sch
arguments.description: Specify the 24-hour weekday schedule.

arguments.name: occupants_weekend_sch
arguments.description: Specify the 24-hour weekend schedule.

arguments.name: occupants_monthly_sch
arguments.description: Specify the 12-month schedule.

measures.name: openstudio_results
measures.description: This measure creates high level tables and charts pulling both from model inputs and EnergyPlus results. It has building level information as well as detail on space types, thermal zones, HVAC systems, envelope characteristics, and economics. Click the heading above a chart to view a table of the chart data.
measures.modeler_description: For the most part consumption data comes from the tabular EnergyPlus results, however there are a few requests added for time series results. Space type and loop details come from the OpenStudio model. The code for this is modular, making it easy to use as a template for your own custom reports. The structure of the report uses bootstrap, and the graphs use dimple js.

arguments.name: units
arguments.display_name: Which Unit System do you want to use?

arguments.name: reg_monthly_details
arguments.display_name: Report monthly fuel and enduse breakdown to registerValue
arguments.description: This argument does not effect HTML file, instead it makes data from individal cells of monthly tables avaiable for machine readable values in the resulting OpenStudio Workflow file.
